      {"question_id":"react_int_004","type":"code_output","question":"What is logged after clicking the button?\n\n```jsx\nfunction App() {\n  const [n, setN] = useState(0);\n  const handleClick = () => {\n    setN(n + 1);\n    setN(n + 1);\n    console.log(n);\n  };\n  return <button onClick={handleClick}>{n}</button>;\n}\n```","options":["2","1","0","undefined"],"correct_answer":2,"explanation":"State updates are asynchronous and batched. Both setN(n+1) use the same stale n=0, so n becomes 1 (not 2). console.log(n) still logs the old value 0 before the re-render. Use functional updates setN(p => p+1) to fix.","difficulty_score":6,"time_seconds":90,"tags":["state_batching","async_state","closures"],"prerequisites":["react_int_001"],"common_mistakes":["Expecting n to be 2 or 1 in the log"],"learning_resources":["https://react.dev/learn/queueing-a-series-of-state-updates"],"real_world_context":"State batching behaviour causes hard-to-debug counters and form update bugs."},
